          "answer": "Ako sa máte?",
          "answerMeaning": "Ako sa máte? = formal. Doctors, officials, landlords and anyone you don't know well use the formal Vy version. Ako sa máš? is only for friends and family."
        },
        {
          "situation": "Your friend asks 'Ako sa máš?' You are doing great. What do you say?",
          "instruction": "Choose the most appropriate response",
          "choices": ["Nie veľmi dobre.", "Som chorý.", "Veľmi dobre, ďakujem!", "Ujde to."],
          "answer": "Veľmi dobre, ďakujem!",
          "answerMeaning": "Veľmi dobre = Very well. Always add ďakujem (thank you) — it sounds natural and polite."
        },
        {
          "situation": "You had a rough week and someone asks how you are. You want to say 'Not very well.' What do you say?",
          "instruction": "Choose the correct phrase",
          "choices": ["Dobre, ďakujem.", "Veľmi dobre.", "Nič nové.", "Nie veľmi dobre."],
          "answer": "Nie veľmi dobre.",
          "answerMeaning": "Nie veľmi dobre = Not very well. Honest and simple. Slovaks appreciate directness."
        },
        {
          "situation": "Your neighbour asks 'Ako sa máte?' You say you are fine and want to ask them back formally. What do you say after 'Dobre, ďakujem'?",
          "instruction": "Choose the correct follow-up",
          "choices": ["A ty?", "Čo je nové?", "A vy?", "Nič nové."],
          "answer": "A vy?",
          "answerMeaning": "A vy? = And you? (formal). Since your neighbour used the formal Vy version, you match it. A ty? is only for friends."
        },
        {
